{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Required patient fields (name, date of birth, insurance ID) are validated before any downstream processing — missing fields produce a clear error listing all missing items.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A pure validator unit test can check missing-field detection, but it can miss a real orchestration failure where downstream modules are still invoked despite validation errors. The failure boundary is request handler/service wiring plus validation gate.","test_description":"Run intake entrypoint with inputs missing multiple required fields; assert response includes all missing field names in one error payload and assert insurance/triage/scheduling adapters are not called.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Date of birth validation rejects future dates, dates more than 150 years ago, and non-date strings.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is local parsing/rule logic with no I/O. Real failures are in date parsing and boundary checks, which are fully catchable at function level.","test_description":"Test DOB validator function with table-driven cases: valid date, future date, >150 years old, malformed string; assert precise validation errors.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The insurance eligibility check sends the correct patient ID and plan code to the payer API and correctly interprets the \"eligible\" vs \"not eligible\" vs \"pending\" response.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"In-process mocks can hide real HTTP/request-shape issues (serialization, parameter placement, headers, status/body parsing). This behavior’s failure boundary includes real HTTP interaction semantics.","test_description":"Use a real HTTP test server endpoint for payer API; execute eligibility call through production HTTP client, assert outbound request contains exact patient ID/plan code contract, and assert response mapping for eligible/not eligible/pending bodies.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the payer API is unreachable, the system marks eligibility as \"pending\" and continues the intake rather than blocking.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Need real transport-failure behavior (connection refused/timeout) at HTTP layer; mocks often under-represent retry/timeout/error-class handling. Continuation behavior must be verified through running pipeline path.","test_description":"Point payer client to a non-routable/refusing endpoint (or force timeout via real HTTP server behavior), run intake flow, assert eligibility is set to pending and downstream triage/scheduling/confirmation still execute.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.73,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The AI symptom triage correctly assigns high urgency to symptom combinations that indicate emergency conditions (e.g., chest pain + shortness of breath).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on model judgment/classification quality, not just wiring. Deterministic mocks would hide real misclassification risk.","test_description":"Run triage against the real AI medical reasoning engine with a curated emergency-case set (including chest pain + shortness of breath); assert urgency classification meets acceptance threshold for high-urgency recall.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The symptom triage produces a natural language explanation of its urgency assessment that a clinician can review, not just a numeric score.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Whether output is clinically reviewable natural language depends on real model generation quality. A mocked/static string would always pass and miss real generation failures.","test_description":"Call real triage model on representative symptom inputs; assert explanation field exists, is non-template natural language text, references key symptoms/rationale, and is not only a numeric or label-only output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"An appointment is scheduled in the first available slot that matches the assigned urgency level — high urgency gets same-day, medium gets within 48 hours.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real risk is in scheduler logic interacting with calendar storage/query ordering. Unit tests can miss DB-backed slot-selection behavior.","test_description":"Seed local calendar DB with occupied/free slots; run scheduling module with high and medium urgency inputs; assert selected slot is earliest valid one and respects same-day/48h constraints.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"The scheduling step does not double-book a time slot even when two patients are being processed concurrently.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is concurrency + shared DB transaction/constraint behavior across modules. In-process single-thread mocks can miss race conditions.","test_description":"Run two concurrent scheduling requests against the same local calendar DB slot using real transaction/locking settings; assert only one booking succeeds for that slot and the other is re-routed or fails gracefully.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.015,"Workflow":0.015}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"The confirmation message includes the patient name, appointment time, provider name, and preparation instructions appropriate to the visit type.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Template-only unit tests can miss data-plumbing failures from scheduling/provider/visit-type modules into confirmation composer.","test_description":"Execute confirmation generation from a persisted appointment record and visit type; assert message contains patient name, appointment time, provider name, and correct prep instructions for that visit type.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"The full intake pipeline — validate, check insurance, triage symptoms, schedule, confirm — completes for a real patient submission without manual intervention.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is end-to-end orchestration across real boundaries (HTTP payer integration behavior, calendar DB persistence, full process flow). The primary risk is cross-component runtime interaction, not a single function.","test_description":"Run a full intake submission through production pipeline wiring with real local DB and real HTTP payer test endpoint (and configured triage service); assert terminal success state, persisted appointment, and emitted confirmation without human fallback path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.05}}]}
